In .NET MAUI, use the **lifecycle events API** in `MauiProgram.cs` (or your app builder setup) via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;

builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
{
#if ANDROID
    events.AddAndroid(android => android
        .OnPause(activity =>
        {
            // Runs when the activity is pausing
        })
        .OnStop(activity =>
        {
            // Runs when the activity is no longer visible
        }));
#endif

#if IOS
    events.AddiOS(ios => ios
        .DidEnterBackground(app =>
        {
            // Runs when the app enters background
        }));
#endif
});
```

**Key points:**

- `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` is called on the `MauiAppBuilder`.
- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code conditional.
- Android exposes `OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnResume`, `OnDestroy`, etc.
- iOS exposes `DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate`, etc.
- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` for the extension methods.

See the [official docs](https://learn.microsoft.com/dotnet/maui/fundamentals/app-lifecycle) for the full list of mapped events per platform.
